social_posts.post_text: 'Guardian Of Your Gifts' (original available) ❤️ My process is super spontaneous and intuitive, but I always return to simple actions whenever I get stuck or want to break out of my style. I choose 3 inspirations to add to my next painting - maybe the yellow orange leaf combo I admired in the trees on my walk, a thin black outline in a Georgia O’Keeffe painting, and the white ink streak I noticed someone added over an eye. This gets my creativity going in new ways and pushes me out of my comfort zone. Then I look at my new painting and choose 3 things I love and add them to my next painting, and keep going from there... sometimes it still leads to me feeling inadequate because I expect to know what I’m doing right away, but, little by little, it takes me somewhere and I usually end up uncovering a new technique that becomes my own.

'Take Flight' (original sold... prints are in my shop) ❤️ Lately I’ve been going back to adding collage elements in my art. I often use papers to create layers, especially when I need to cover up an area I don’t like. It’s an easy way to fill in the space and add detail. I love using origami and lokta papers that have intricate patterns and metallics (they can be found at many art stores, craft stores and paper stores). Napkins are so fun for adding pattern too – the decorative paper napkins you can find with butterflies and landscapes on them in intricate designs. They always bring a little lightness and magic into my paintings (something I can’t always bring out with my other mixed media supplies). But my favorite papers are the ones I stumble upon in my everyday – maps and sheet music from antique shops, gift wrap and tissue in a gift from a friend or even old diaries. I always keep an eye out in unexpected places.

I love looking back at past work for inspiration ❤️ I hope these paintings bring you inspiration and beauty too!

Then I keep those small elements in mind and add them to my painting. This helps to keep it simple.

‘Dreams Come True’ 11” x 14” (original available) ❤️ Every painting has a name and I always love coming up with their titles. I keep a note on my phone and any time I hear a phrase or word that resonates I write it down to come back to when I’m coming up with a title. But mostly, when I finish a painting, I sit with my journal and stare into the eyes and wait for words to come. I generally write down a list of twenty words. As I write the words, certain ones begin to fit together or come up again. I don’t question it or judge, I keep going and can feel myself getting closer and closer, narrowing down what the painting is saying until finally, like the final brushstroke on a painting, I take a breath and know I’ve found the title. It’s a super intuitive process and helps me connect deeper to each painting.

A few years ago I wrote a 300 page manuscript about enchanted fairytales. I wasn’t painting at the time. I hadn’t painted in years. All of my artwork had ended up in the basement. I didn’t see any point in painting anymore and locked away that part of myself. Yet I had to create something, so I started writing a novel as I worked full-time in an office (at a job I really hated). I was one of 14 writers accepted into a writing workshop on the east coast. I even flew out to Washington DC to meet with my ideal literary agent. But then I stopped. My creative spirit was stunted from all of the writing critiques and constructive criticism. I had been convinced that because my voice was different, it wasn’t right. So I’d written a novel that wasn’t truly from my heart and I completely got burned out. To get my spirit back, I returned to what I loved most as a child – painting in my backyard. And that's what started all of my whimsical paintings. It all led to a life and career I never would have imagined.

As I’m covering up parts of my painting, I try and keep my painting in balance. This makes it easier for the piece to feel like it’s fitting together. The main thing I do to achieve balance is that if I do something in one section of the painting, I do the same thing somewhere else too. So if I make my background green, I add a little green to my character. If I add big polka dots in the lower right corner, I’ll add a few small polka dots in the upper right.

'Guardian Of Hope And Light' (original sold... prints are in my shop) ❤️ If I’m not liking my art, I have to cover it up. It’s usually the eyes or face that I don’t like, so I’ll often dump water on top and smudge the features out. This leaves some of the eyes and features behind and gives me a new place to begin, but since I can still see some old outlines, it’s a way to continue what was already there and try again. If after a few tries I still don’t like the face, I’ll redraw the character with their eyes closed. This is one of the easiest ways to fix a character and instantly gives calm to any art. Even if that’s not what you see in the finished piece, it usually softens my character enough so I can feel that same softness in my own heart and begin to move forward, painting from a place of joy. Once I like my painting again, I feel more confident. Sometimes all I need is to return to that comfort zone so I can stop thinking so much and really get into a flow.

I wasn’t liking the painting, so I dumped water on top and it smudged all of my pencil lines... now I keep trying to repeat that same beautiful drip that happened over her body. 

Whenever I'm having fun, that's when the magic happens… and that’s what inspired her title too. I hope she can be an inspiration to you today for finding your own joy and freedom. Have a wonderful Thursday!

Whenever I'm stuck with my art, I don’t let myself look at any other artwork. If I do, I start to compare myself to everyone else and waste so much time “getting inspired” that I feel paralyzed. Instead, I play with water-soluble oil pastels in one of my coloring books or sketch a little owl to let go. I keep it simple. That way, when I come back to painting my characters, my creativity is open and free for mess making.

Looking back at these past paintings today as a little reminder that every painting I create takes lots (and lots) of layers… and so often when I’m in the messy middle, I want to cover the whole thing up 💖 All of these original paintings have sold, but prints are available in my shop (the link is in my profile @juliettecrane ) ❤️ I hope they bring you a little extra inspiration and beauty today too!

'Lullaby' (original sold... prints are in my shop) ❤️ Whenever I paint with friends, it reminds me to always take time for myself and always do what brings me joy. For me that means slowing down and keeping calm, reading in the sunshine, stepping outside at midnight to watch for shooting stars, doodling, taking long walks in the woods, having bonfires in the backyard, going barefoot in the grass, smelling the flowers and painting with friends and family. More than anything I am reminded that my every day is a process with one thing leading to the next. That there is no right or wrong way.

Tell me some of your favorite things...

But I've learned to allow the weird and wonky bits of me, the imperfections, mistakes and color experiments to stand out. I've learned to be okay with being unique so I can let go. Then I can remember to be kinder to myself and have more fun with my art.

‘Trust’ 12” x 16” (original sold) ❤️ I loved using sumi ink for my black lines in my paintings. I’ve been looking back at a few past paintings for inspiration on the new large paintings I’m working on and I’m constantly reminded of how I begin to create soulful eyes ♥️ 

One of the techniques I use to paint more deep, open eyes, is to start with a few fingerprints or simple dots. Then I use a water-soluble pencil to draw details and smudge out the lines with a little paint or water, so my initial layers show through. This creates the illusion of definition, but with lots of depth and softness. It also helps me loosen up and let go.

Today’s prompt is: INSPIRATION ✨

I started writing my fiction novel before I was painting my whimsical characters in my late twenties because I had this story inside. But I didn’t read books at that time. 

I wasn’t a reader as a child. Instead I turned to art. But once I started writing a novel, I looked for inspiration and found @neilhimself 🙌 I was lucky enough to live in Chicago at the time and went to a ton of author readings. Some of the first poetry books I picked up were Emily Dickinson and E.E. Cummings and I still come back to them. 

But it wasn’t until I got burned out on writing and turned back to painting that I really started to read for pure joy and relaxation. 

Now that’s brought me back to writing poems, fiction and nonfiction again. I read a book a week… and am currently reading everything by @rebeccamakkai ♥️

I’m also inspired by stories and watching people and hearing about their passions and their lives. My hope is that you feel a little bit of that connectedness and connection in my art and writing too 🦋

I’m working on a few writing projects right now, so I’m taking part in the #meetthewriter challenge with the beautiful author @bethkempton (love her book The Way of the Fearless Writer) ✍️🩵

Today’s prompt is: DREAM✨

I love to travel. My husband and I were engaged in Florence, Italy ~ he proposed in the Boboli Gardens ~ and I’ve always wanted to go back 🌞✨

My dream writing and painting retreat would be a villa in Tuscany with views of the countryside.

I would be overlooking the hills and shade from the sun. Behind me would sit the house, gardens and a pool. There’d be a stone terrace with a trellis overflowing with pink blooms and a big wooden table where I could create.

I’d set up my easel and paint. Then sit at the table and write. Off to the side, there’d be a cozy reading nook with cushioned sofas or maybe a hammock.

✍️ My creativity flows best when I can move from one creative endeavor to the next - whether that’s writing at a table, painting at an easel, reading 📚 or taking a swim or a walk. I love having one big project to work on, but I also love the flow of moving from one creative act to the next. 

As one idea percolates for my writing, I paint and get into that flow, then move back to writing for a bit, until I paint again 🎨 It’s similar to how I work on many paintings at once at different stages. 

Once I add my writing, researching and inspiration gathering into the process, it’s the most beautiful flow 🙌

What is your dream space to be creative?

Sometimes there’s just no logic to living a creative life. It’s so much about staying open and being present, following your instincts and intuition. 

So much of my creative process is in the mystery. Oftentimes it feels like nothing is working. I’ll just be brainstorming and write a bunch of poetry, add words to a watercolor painting or write a story about my process and wonder what on earth I’m doing. 

But there’s so much beauty in the unknown and in the wandering, yet there’s also frustration, especially when I try to hurry up the process. 

What I’m starting to see is that my entire life and living are creative. Even when I feel off track, like I’m not accomplishing anything, it’s the journey. 

Then suddenly there’s a finished painting in front of me or a story. A book proposal or even a finished novel. It’s only at that point where I can see how all of the pieces finally fit together 🙌

One of the things I’ve been paying attention to lately are the similarities between my writing and painting practice. 

My paintings always involve lots of layers - I begin with a colorful background, then sketch my face and character, fill in with more color, and then go back and forth between adding more layers, messing everything up, and adding more detail. 

It’s the same process with my writing, whether I’m writing a newsletter or my novel. 

It starts with a big burst of lots of ideas just to get everything down. Then lots of editing and revisions to get to the core message. 

I love how with creative process one thing just flows into the next ~ it all becomes energy for living a more creative life ✍️🎨

I recently found progress photos from these paintings (I’m excited to share them with you soon!) ♥️

It was such a good reminder that every painting has an ugly stage and tons of mistakes along the way.

Having progress photos of my past paintings also helps me understand what worked and what didn't. Then I can use those ideas and inspirations for whatever I’m working on at the moment. It helps me to see everything differently and remember my process. 

Because oftentimes in the moment that I’m creating I forget. Not just that I always run into creative blocks, but I also forget the techniques and tricks I turn back to whenever I want to move a painting forward. 

Things may not turn out the same way, but at least the inspirations are in my arsenal of techniques that I can pull from whenever I get frustrated or overwhelmed. Then that painting process flows and my creativity flies free.

I can be brave and paint without the pressure of everything having to be perfect, allowing me to approach my artwork with joy. That's when the magic happens ✨🎨

It doesn’t matter if you just painted something in your sketchbook and turned the page. You never know where that might lead. You just might end up brightening someone’s day 🦋

All of my paintings begin with a few abstract layers of color. It’s my way to loosen up, but also I can never quite begin on a blank, white canvas. 

The drips and first layers become an open doorway so I can see where to go next with a painting.

So the other day I set up a painting station in my backyard outside my studio - I covered up a few blank canvases with color, dripped inks and splattered acrylics, then added loads of water to create my first layers. I even got out my watering can to splash and create puddles that dries like stained glass. 

This is my favorite way to let go and play with my paintings. It’s one of the things I come back to whenever I need to find my creative flow. Because sometimes I just can’t find that freedom. 

But then, after a beautiful mistakes and a little loosening up with color, my creativity blooms just like the flowers in my garden.

Someone asked the other day how I came up with the hair for my portraits of women. And, while it started with a few circles in the first layers of my paintings, this hairstyle is actually a dramatization of how I sometimes wear my own hair.

Whenever I paint, I like to wrap my hair around chopsticks to keep it up – I used to have these wonderful wooden chopsticks with carved giraffes on the ends so you could see the little ears peeking up (I wish I still had those).

When I started adding this wild hair to my paintings, it came out of a new technique I developed for my first layers – painting circles with inks and acrylic paints.

I wanted to emulate the flocked wallpaper my grandparents had in their living room and bathrooms.

Since I’m not into drawing details in my paintings (except when it comes to painting eyes and faces), I abstracted the flocked wallpaper patterns, beginning with a pattern of circles, then outlining each circle.

It all becomes a meditative process.

Then, when I sketched in the face, the wild hair fell right into place. I like to imagine they are queens and princesses inhabiting their own fairytale lands.

I wrote more about the process and how I developed my style in my latest blog post (the link is in my stories and bio). I hope it’s inspiring for you!

This week I’ve been looking back at some of my favorite ways to create first layers for my paintings. 

All of my paintings begin with a few abstract first layers of color. It’s my way to loosen up, but also I can never quite begin on a blank, white canvas. 

These backgrounds always inspire the direction on the painting, so I like to stay really deliberate with the techniques and supplies I use, and then let go. 

One of my favorite techniques for these first layers is to pretend I’m painting an abstract - you can see this in yesterday’s painting reel 🎨✨ This creates all sorts of organic shapes and color combinations. I love to just brush the color on wildly, leaving the imperfections. 

Some of my favorite supplies to use include acrylics, inks, spray paint, chalk pastels, water-soluble oil pastels and watercolors (often all together).

There can never be a wrong way and it’s so fun to just smoosh the color around and see what happens.

I wrote more about my process for painting luscious layers and shared some tips on how to avoid making a muddy mess - it’s all over on my blog today (the link is in my bio and stories). I hope it’s inspiring for you!

Hello, friends 🩵 I recently joined Substack and I’d love to connect with you there… it’ll be my place to write and share more in-depth with you about my art, process, and creative living.

Years ago, when I was hopping from job to job, feeling like there was no way I’d ever get back to painting again, I dreamed of living a full-time creative life. It wasn’t until I was fired in 2009 from the only job I ever really liked - as a landscaper here in Wisconsin - that I finally started painting again to heal my heart.

I didn’t think anyone would want to see my art, let alone buy it. But when friends stopped by, they said they liked my work. I finally got up the courage to ask at our local library and exhibited my art the next month. I invited family, friends, and friends of friends to a little opening. That’s how I sold my first two originals to people I didn’t know. The library also purchased a piece for their permanent collection. A few people asked for prints and cards, so I started selling those too.

Little by little, it all gave me the confidence to take another step and share more. I signed up for an online creative business course in 2008 and started a blog. And that was what began my whimsical paintings and a creative life I love.

Recently, I’ve been longing for more of that old school creative community again. I kept hearing about this new space called Substack. So, I thought I’d give it a try and share a bit more of the behind-the-scenes of life as a full-time artist, writer, and creative educator living with my bluegrass-singing husband on 10 acres of magical pine woods in the countryside of Wisconsin.

Thank you to Holly Becker of @decor8 and her Blogging Today class and community for inspiring me to give this a go.

My paintings happen in many layers. Sometimes they take a few days to finish. Others take a few weeks (especially my larger pieces). But I always make sure to let my color dry in between layers. That way the colors remain super vibrant and true.

A template I often follow in my first layers is to add a layer of one color hue, say mostly blues or mostly reds and pinks. Then, once that first layer dries, I like to add a translucent color on top, say a cadmium yellow acrylic ink mixed with a neon pink high flow acrylic paint.

That way, I not only avoid making brown but also get so much variation and luminosity from the layers.

I’m sharing more of my secrets for layering color over on Substack - the link to read more is in my profile and in my stories.

My creative process is all about staying loose, so I always play and experiment in my first layers, and then build upon them as I continue the painting. I also often find myself setting aside my brushes and focusing on finger painting. 

This keeps me unattached to my painting, preventing me from getting into my head and “thinking” the eyes and face should look a certain way or be a certain shape. It allows for imperfections and beautiful mistakes.

The eyes are always the hardest thing for me to paint. It takes lots and lots of layers and different art supplies to get them right. But I can never stop until they resonate with my heart. 

The eyes of my characters are what lead me into the rest of the painting. If you want to paint open eyes and you’re looking to keep them looking soulful, try using lots of different art supplies for your layers. 

I like to begin with a black water-soluble pencil to draw my initial features. Then I smudge out the lines with a little acrylic paint or water, letting these first layers bleed out to create shading and definition. 

Next I go back in with some colored paint pen, then acrylic ink and more acrylic paint. Each layer is a back and forth between creating definition, messing it up so it’s not too perfect, then adding more detail and definition again.

I was in a serious slump in my early 20s. I’d graduated from college with degrees in fine arts and journalism, landing a ‘dream’ job at an arts newspaper in the city. However, working in an office crushed my spirit.

During my lunch breaks, I found solace in a West African restaurant. The owner, aware of my artistic inclination, and I would talk for hours while she introduced me to various foods – plantains and jollof rice, fufu and peanut stew. 

Soon, I was spending entire afternoons there, and no one at work seemed to notice.

So, when the restaurant owner asked if I wanted to go to Ghana in four weeks, I said sure. Somehow, I managed to get my visa, renew my passport, took a month off of work, and was on my way.

That trip to Africa changed my life forever 💛
